                    <div class="approach-algorithm">
   In a normal singly linked list deletion, we need access to the previous node so we can update its pointer to skip the node being deleted. But in this problem, we are not given the head of the list, so we cannot reach the previous node. Instead, we are directly given the node that needs to be deleted, and it is guaranteed that this node is not the tail node. <br><br>The trick here is that if we cannot remove the current node directly, we can copy the data of its next node into it and delete the next node instead. This way, the current node takes the identity of the next node, and the linked list remains valid.
   <ul>
       <li>Take the given node that needs to be deleted.</li>
       <li>Copy the value from the next node into the current node.</li>
       <li>Update the current node’s next pointer to skip over the next node.</li>
       <li>This effectively removes the next node, achieving the deletion of the given node.</li>

   </ul>
